Feature-level fusion, also known as intermediate-level fusion, is a computational approach that combines multiple feature vectors from different origins or stages of the neural network into a single representation. Unlike low-level fusion, which simply concatenates raw data and, in the case of large datasets containing not only useful information but also noise and other details, amplifies redundancy and computational load, this approach uses methods such as linear projection, attention mechanisms, and normalization to mitigate problems of redundancy, scaling imbalance, and high dimensionality. This paradigm has been validated across various applications, ranging from remote sensing and mineralogy to food safety, medical diagnostics and plastic waste sorting.